    <string name="menu_pip_adb_title">Unlock PIP via ADB</string>
    <string name="dialog_pip_adb_guide_title">Picture-in-Picture ADB Instructions</string>
    <string name="dialog_pip_adb_guide_text"><![CDATA[
Some TV manufacturers block Picture-in-Picture (PiP) by default. Execute these steps to permanently unlock it:<br><br>
1. Enable Developer Options on the TV (click 7x on "Build Number" in the system settings).<br>
2. Enable "ADB Debugging" in the developer options.<br>
3. Open a command prompt on your PC and connect to the TV:<br>
<tt><b>adb connect [YOUR_TV_IP]:5555</b></tt><br><br>
4. Copy and execute the following command exactly:<br>
<tt><b>adb shell appops set com.shipofagony.klippshell4creality PICTURE_IN_PICTURE allow</b></tt><br><br>
<tt><b>adb shell appops set com.shipofagony.klippshell4creality SYSTEM_ALERT_WINDOW allow</b></tt><br><br>
<tt><b>adb shell dumpsys deviceidle whitelist +com.shipofagony.klippshell4creality</b></tt><br><br>
5. Restart the KlippShell app on the TV. PiP is now permanently ready for use!<br><br>
Or simply use the KlippShellHelper extension:<br>
<tt>https://github.com/Ship-of-Agony/KlippShell-Helper<tt>
]]></string>

    <string name="overlay_permission_title">Display over other apps</string>
    <string name="overlay_permission_desc">Since some TV devices block native Picture-in-Picture (PiP), KlippShell requires this permission as a fallback. This allows the app to display a stable, floating mini-window over other TV apps (like Netflix or Prime), ensuring you can always monitor your printer status while watching TV. Please enable KlippShell in the following system settings.</string>
    <string name="overlay_permission_btn">Enable Now</string>

